    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking at some Cessna maintenance docs. Can you explain the actual physics of how a pitot tube works to measure airspeed? Also, why is it such a big deal if the opening gets blocked?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the pitot tube, a trusty little device that measures the airspeed of your trusty Cessna, much like a clever little elf measuring the wind speed to determine the best time to fly off to the next adventure. The pitot tube works by capturing the dynamic pressure of the air flowing into it, which is then compared to the static pressure of the surrounding air. This difference in pressure is what tells us the airspeed, much like how a wise old wizard might read the wind's whispers to predict the weather.\n\nNow, if the opening of the pitot tube gets blocked, it's like a mischievous goblin has thrown a wrench into the works. The air can't flow freely into the tube, and the readings become inaccurate, much like trying to read a map with a torn piece missing. This can lead to dangerous situations, as the pilot might not know the true speed of the aircraft, much like a goblin trying to navigate through a forest without a compass. So, it's crucial to keep that opening clear, lest we find ourselves in a sticky situation.",
